Title of research study: Emotion & Cognitive Abilities

 

Investigators: Catherine J. Norris, Ph.D.

 

Why am I being invited to take part in a research study?

We invite you to take part in a research study because you are an American adult over the age of 18 living in the United States.



What should I know about a research study?

·       Instructions on the web-based survey will explain this research study to you.

·       Whether or not you take part is up to you.

·       You can choose not to take part.

·       You can agree to take part and later change your mind.

·       Your decision will not be held against you.

·       You can ask all the questions you want before you decide.

 

Who can I talk to?

If you have questions, concerns, or complaints, or think the research has hurt you, talk to the research team by contacting Prof. Catherine J. Norris at cnorris2@swarthmore.edu.



This research has been reviewed and approved by an Institutional Review Board (“IRB”). You may talk to them at (610) 957-6150 or irb@swarthmore.edu if:

·       Your questions, concerns, or complaints are not being answered by the research team.

·       You cannot reach the research team.

·       You want to talk to someone besides the research team.

·       You have questions about your rights as a research subject.

·       You want to get information or provide input about this research.

 

Why is this research being done?

We are interested in how emotions affect how different people perform simple cognitive tasks.



Risks & Benefits

There are no risks beyond what an individual would encounter in an everyday setting. You may view some images that are emotionally evocative, but they should not be traumatizing in any way.



There are no direct benefits to participants engaging with this research project.

 

How long will the research last?

We expect that you will be in this research study for about XX minutes.

 

How many people will be studied?

We expect about XXXX people in the entire study.

 

What happens if I say yes, I want to be in this research?

This research involves a few different tasks: watching a film clip, answering questions about the film clip, performing a few simple computerized tasks, and answering some questions about you. You will receive a unique code word at the conclusion of the survey to submit to Amazon Mechanical Turk to receive payment. Participation is voluntary and anonymous. No identifying information is requested and your responses will be combined with thousands of other subjects and reported as aggregate data.

 

What happens if I do not want to be in this research?

You can leave the research at any time and it will not be held against you.

 

What happens if I say yes, but I change my mind later?

You can leave the research at any time it will not be held against you. In the event you withdraw from the study, you will not receive payment.

 

What happens to the information collected for the research?

No identifying information is requested and your responses will be combined with hundreds of other subjects and reported as aggregate data. The data will be stored on a secure, encrypted server. Efforts will be made to limit the use and disclosure of your personal information to people who have a need to review this information. We cannot promise complete secrecy. Organizations that may inspect and copy your information include the IRB and other representatives of this organization.

 

Exemption of Signed Informed Consent

This research was reviewed by the IRB and found to meet exemption criteria set forth in regulation.

 

Informed Consent Block for Capable Adult

It makes me feel even more grateful for my continuous happiness yet sad for others that are less fortunate.
